### Description

tsconfig.paths  configuration doesn't applied to library's import path. 

### Minimal Reproduction

Here is the minimal repro case. 
I publish two libraries called `@com/print-js`, `@com/styled-components`.

In `@com/print-js` library, it use InjectionToken from `@com/styled-components` library. 
```
import { SOME_TOKEN } from '@com/styled-components';

@Injectable() 
export class PrintService {
    appConfig = inject(SOME_TOKEN); 
}
```

In my main project, 
it includes all files of `@com/styled-components` library codes and link the code directly by using path mapping config.
```
"paths": {
   "@com/styled-components": [ 
      "../../styled-components/src/index.ts", 
   ],
},
```

And then, i use `PrintService` from `@com/print-js` library in standalone component. 
```
import { PrintModule }  from '@com/print-js'; 

@Component({
   selector: 'comp',
   standalone: true,
   imports: [
      PrintModule, // which include PrintService 
   ],
   ...
}) 
export class Component {
    print = inject(PrintService); 
}
```

When i serve the main project with ESBuild, it raise error 
```
✘ [ERROR] Could not resolve "@com/styled-components"

    node_modules/@mapiacompany/print-js/fesm2022/mapiacompany-print-js.mjs:5:36:
      5 │ import { SOME_TOKEN } from '@com/styled-components';
        ╵                                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  You can mark the path "@com/styled-components" as external to exclude it from the bundle, which will remove this error and leave the unresolved path in the bundle.
```

With webpack serve, it works well. (correctly path mapping to `../../styled-components/src/index.ts` code)

